bug.short_desc: Component model does not handle special chars in project names

long_desc.thetext:
Created attachment 86395 the exception was thrown
Build ID: Build id: 20070926042742
Steps To Reproduce: 1.Start File -> New -> Project... -> EJB -> EJB Project 2.Set name, which contains # or % 3.Press "Finish" button The project is created, but the resources are missing, and the attached exception thrown.
More information: Hello,
When I’m trying to create a faceted project, which names contains #, I’m receiving an error, and the relevant facet doesn't installed correct the required resources. I found the reason is that the symbol # is fragment separator in accordance with RFC 2396 (Uniform Resource Identifiers (URI): Generic Syntax). I did attempts what is happening with other excluded symbols from the URI specification (vol. 2.4.3 on http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc2396.txt) and the behavior was different. If the name of the project was containing %, I did receive the same error, but the project was created successfully. For the other symbols (<,> and “), the wizard shown the warning message (for instance : < is an invalid character in resource name 'TE<ST'.)
Could you implement the relevant check for the excluded symbols # and % in order to avoid this bug, please?
Best Regards, Dimiter

It is legal for a project name to have # and % characters.
Chuck,
Sending this your way. Looks like a problem with component model not handling these characters correctly. Please re-assign as appropriate.
I will take a look at this issue.

Created attachment 107451 exception
up-to-date exception that is thrown with the latest 3.0.1 I-build.

Created attachment 107453 patch jem.util
It seems the root of the problem is that org.eclipse.emf.common.util.URI objects are created with the project name, but the String that constructs the URI is not encoded. Therefore, special characters like '#' produce incorrect URI.
This patch fixes the construction of URI in jem.util's WorkbenchURIConverterImpl and WorkbenchResourceHelperBase classes. As result the previous exception is no more experienced.

The usage of the deprecated URI.createPlatformResourceURI() method, that is resolved in the 'patch jem.util' is used in many places in the WTP code. It should be addressed in wtp-dev mailing list developers to review their code for such usages.
